column3: Department of Mechanical Engineering and Materials Science
column8: weixiong@pitt.edu   Abstract    Stacking fault energy (SFE) is vital in controlling the deformation mechanism and mechanical properties  of austenitic steels
column9: while there are no accurate and straightforward computational tools for modeling it.To  address this issue
column10: we evaluate the CALPHAD-based thermodynamic models (CALPHAD: calculations of  phase diagrams)
column11: analyze the alloying effect on SFE using data analytics
column12: and present how machine learning  (ML) accurately predicts the SFE of austenitic steels.The results show that ML is more precise and flexible  compared to thermodynamic and empirical models.

column1: This work demonstrates the capability of ML to predict  material properties when physical models and experiments are unfeasible.     Keywords: Machine learning
column4: CALPHAD      Designing  alloys  with  high  strength  and  excellent  ductility  is  one  of  the  ultimatums  to  be  achieved  in  materials  research. A  plausible  solution  to  achieve  this  goal  is  introducing  the  secondary  deformation  mechanisms
column5: including twinning-induced plasticity (TWIP) and transformation-induced plasticity (TRIP)
column6: which continuously improve the strength and ductility during deformation [1

column1: Stacking fault energy (SFE)  is  the  energy  related  to  dissociating  a  perfect  dislocation  into  two  partial  dislocations  along  with  the  formation of a stacking fault.SFE is an accurate indicator to predict which type of secondary deformation  mechanism  operates. Generally
column2: TRIP  activates  when  SFE  is  lower  than  20  mJ/m2  [3]  and  TWIP  is  achievable  if  the  SFE  lies  between  20  â€“  40  mJ/m2  [4].
various  efforts  have  been  made  to  determine the SFE of different alloys.Experimental methods
column3: including transmission electron microscopy  [5â€“7] and X-Ray/Neutron diffraction [8
column5: are tedious and difficult which delay the process of exploring  new  materials. Computational  methods  such  as  empirical  equations
column6: ab  initio  calculations  and  thermodynamic models serve as an alternative solution.

column2: various empirical equations have been  proposed [10â€“16]
column3: they predict conflicting effects for different alloying elements on SFE.This is because  they  are  localized  for  a  confined  composition  space  and  cannot  be  extrapolated  for  other  steels. A  thermodynamic model was proposed by Olson et al [17]
column4: and has been adapted in many works [18â€“21].

column2: an intrinsic stacking fault is defined as an hcp phase with two boundaries shared with  the  fcc  matrix. However
column3: the  thermodynamic  model  involves  many  parameters  and  varies  in  different  reports. Also
column4: and  none  of  the  thermodynamic  models  have  been  verified  for  alloys  with  a  broader  composition  range  [18

column3: 25]  are  difficult  due  to  the  chemical  and  magnetic disorder in complex alloys
column4: and certain works underestimate the SFE and report negative values  [26
column6: they are sometimes limited in predicting trends rather than the accurate value of SFE.  A promising way to leverage the wealth of data and circumvent the difficulty of SFE prediction is applying  data-driven  methods.

column1: Machine learning  (ML)  is  useful  in  extracting  knowledge  from  multi-dimensional  data and modeling the relationships between the targeted property and its related features [28].In recent  years
column2: there are few studies that applied ML for SFE prediction [29
column3: 30].Das [29] predicted SFE using an  artificial neural network (ANN) with 100 compositions as an input.

column2: that work did not incorporate  temperature into the model and ANN requires an extensive database for generating a reliable model
column3: which  may limit the accuracy of this work.Chaudhary et al [30] built a classifier that categorizes compositions   into  high

column3: and  building  an  accurate  SFE  predictor  are  imperative. In  this  paper
column4: the  following  has  been  accomplished:  1)  established  a  database  containing the composition and SFE of various steels
column5: 2) assessed the CALPHAD-based thermodynamic  model (CALPHAD: calculations of phase diagrams)

column7: and 4) predicted SFE using ML.The performance of the ML model developed in this work is superior  to  the  thermodynamic  and  empirical  models.
